description.narrative: Secondary schools have capacity to support girls' learning and are safe, affordable and provide relevant life-skills, which contributes to Children With Disabilities, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Equitable Access To Quality Education (Covid), Gender Discriminatory Roles And Practices, Learning Outcomes. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: School-aged girls and boys, especially early adolescents (aged 10-14) [in targeted districts], acquire essential learning outcomes and practice skills for life, are safe from exploitation, harmful practices and violence, and benefit from integrated social services (including in emergencies).

description.narrative: Malawian children can now access tuition fee free secondary school following the enforcement of the Tuition Free Secondary Education Policy. A total of 11,107 girls benefited from UNICEF supported bursaries and scholarships to offset other school-related costs like uniforms, learning materials and boarding costs through the recently established National Girls Trust Fund (NGTF), which continued to leverage additional funding through numerous partnerships including the private sector. UNICEF leveraged support from World Bank, EU and USAID to collaborate on improving secondary education programming in Malawi. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:12/12/2019
